Formula 1 | Monaco Grand Prix 2021 | Fernando Alonso

Formula 1 | Monaco Grand Prix 2021 | Fernando Alonso

Baptiste Gorteau & Th√©o Cavenne

1 Introduction

For several years now, data has been a regular feature of sport. Formula 1 is one of those sports where, in addition to being present, data plays a crucial role in the performance of drivers and cars. We wanted to observe these data-driven variations in performance for ourselves. To this end, we collected Fernando Alonso‚Äôs race data for the Monaco Grand Prix in 2021, using the Formula One Api. Our work will focus on studying Fernando Alonso‚Äôs speed during his various laps using signal analysis techniques.

2 Data description

For this project, we decided to study Fernando Alonso‚Äôs speed at the Monaco Formula 1 Grand Prix in 2021.

The datasets we will use are the following :

  • laps.csv : Summary with different information for each lap driven by Fernando Alonso (lap time, lap number, type of tires used, etc). The only variables we‚Äôll be using in this dataset are ‚ÄúLapNumber‚Äù (lap number), ‚ÄúPitOutTime‚Äù and ‚ÄúPitInTime‚Äù (times when Alonso entered or left the pits). We‚Äôll call this dataset ‚Äúlaps_alonso‚Äù.
laps_alonso <- read.csv("Data/ALO/laps.csv")
print((laps_alonso %>% select(LapNumber,PitOutTime,PitInTime))[c(1,45,46),])
##    LapNumber             PitOutTime              PitInTime
## 1          1 0 days 00:00:04.827000                       
## 45        45                        0 days 01:31:34.693000
## 46        46 0 days 01:31:58.267000
  • lap_i.0.csv (for i ranging from 1 to 77): Here we have 77 different data sets, each representing a lap of the Monaco GP 2021 driven by Fernando Alonso. For each of these data sets (laps), we‚Äôll have several Distance/Speed pairs representing the speed measured at a precise distance from the starting line for a lap. We‚Äôll concatenate these 77 datasets to produce a single dataframe (24861 rows and 3 columns) comprising the variables ‚ÄúDistance‚Äù (distance in meters from the starting line of the speed measurement point), ‚ÄúSpeed‚Äù (speed in km/h measured) and ‚Äúlap‚Äù (lap number (1 to 77)). We‚Äôll call this data set ‚ÄúALO‚Äù.
ALO <- read.csv(paste("Data/ALO/tours/lap_1.0.csv",sep = "")) %>% select(Distance,Speed) %>% mutate(lap=1)
for(i in 2:length(laps_alonso$LapNumber)){
  lap <- read.csv(paste("Data/ALO/tours/lap_",i,".0.csv",sep = "")) %>% select(Distance,Speed) %>% mutate(lap=i)
  ALO <- rbind(ALO,lap)
}

The speed representations for each turn appear to be regular and non-periodic. We have therefore decided not to study the Fourier and wavelet bases. In the following, we shall concentrate on cubic spline bases.

3 Choosing nodes for the cubic spline base

3.1 First base

On the curve representation above, we can see that there are 24 ‚Äúabrupt‚Äù changes (peaks) between acceleration and deceleration. We therefore decided to choose our nodes ‚Äúby hand‚Äù. The 24 nodes chosen represent the distances of the entrances and exits of these bends (relative to the starting line).

knots <- c(75,220,575,780,835,900,1020,1115,1180,1245,1290,1325,1360,1415,1900,2090,2260,2355,2565,2705,2785,2880,2930,2975)
knots <- c(xrange[1],knots,xrange[2])

Here we have a 4th-order spline basis with 24 interior nodes and therefore 28 basis functions :

bspbasis = create.bspline.basis(xrange,norder=4,breaks=knots)
  • Projection of individual curves onto the selected spline base :
laps = unique(ALO$lap)
nb_laps = length(laps)
CoeffMat = matrix(0,nrow=nb_laps,ncol=bspbasis$nbasis)
for (i in 1:nb_laps){
  decomp = Data2fd(ALO$Distance[ALO$lap==laps[i]],ALO$Speed[ALO$lap==laps[i]],basisobj = bspbasis)
  CoeffMat[i,] = as.vector(decomp$coefs)
}

alo.smooth = fd(t(CoeffMat),bspbasis)

We note that 2 ‚Äúabrupt‚Äù changes between acceleration and deceleration‚Äù are missing between 1100 and 1450, and 2 between 2275 and 3000.

3.2 Second base

We‚Äôll reuse the same base, adding 5 extra nodes in each of these intervals (so adding 10 nodes in total). In this case, we‚Äôll have a base of 4th-order splines with 34 interior nodes and therefore 38 basis functions.

Visualization of smoothed curves :

knots <- sort(c(knots,seq(1100,1450,length=5),seq(2775,3000,length=5)))

bspbasis = create.bspline.basis(xrange,norder=4,breaks=knots)

CoeffMat = matrix(0,nrow=nb_laps,ncol=bspbasis$nbasis)
for (i in 1:nb_laps){
  decomp = Data2fd(ALO$Distance[ALO$lap==laps[i]],ALO$Speed[ALO$lap==laps[i]],basisobj = bspbasis)
  CoeffMat[i,] = as.vector(decomp$coefs)
}
alo.smooth = fd(t(CoeffMat),bspbasis)  
plot(alo.smooth,xlab="Distance",ylab="Speed",main="Smoothed curves")

We find these representations very satisfactory. We shall therefore retain the spline base created above for the remainder of this section.

4 Exploratory statistics

4.1 Study of functional mean and standard deviation


fhat <- eval.fd(seq(xrange[1],xrange[2],length.out=325),alo.smooth)
mean_lap <- mean.fd(alo.smooth)
sd_lap <- sd.fd(alo.smooth)
plot(alo.smooth,col="gray",xlab="distance",ylab="speed", main = "Mean and variance of smoothed laps")
lines(mean_lap)
lines(mean_lap+2*sd_lap,lwd=2,col=4,lty=2)
lines(mean_lap-2*sd_lap,lwd=2,col=4,lty=2)
legend("bottomleft",legend = c("Mean", "Variance", "lap"), col=c("black", "blue", "gray"), lty=c(1,2,2), cex=0.8)

The graph shows that most of the curves lie within the variance range. Greater variance can be observed at moments of change between acceleration and deceleration (local maximums and minimums). On the contrary, for the rest of the time, speed varies very little between laps. It is interesting to note that the variance at braking is higher when braking is strong (comparison between braking at 1700m and at 2500m).

4.2 Functional PCA


ACPF = pca.fd(alo.smooth,nharm=2,centerfns = TRUE)
ACPF$varprop
## [1] 0.3705133 0.1664614
cumsum(ACPF$varprop)
## [1] 0.3705133 0.5369747

Here, the first two principal components explain 54% of the data.

par(mfrow=c(1,2), pin = c(2, 2))
plot(mean_lap, main ="Average of smoothed curves", ylab="Speed", xlab="Distance")
plot(ACPF$harmonics, main="Main components", ylab="Explanation", xlab="Distance")
legend("topright", legend = c("Component 1", "Component 2"), col=c("black", "red"), lty=1:2, cex=0.5)

The graph on the right shows the representations of the principal components of the PCA performed. The black curve is the one that captures the most information on the data. This same curve separates the data according to the first kilometer and the sector around 2.5km.

This graph shows that axis 2 separates lap 48 from the other laps. Let‚Äôs take a look at which turn it was.

plot(mean_lap, xlab = "Distance (m)", ylab="Speed", main = "Comparison of lap 48 speed with average speed.")
lines(ALO[ALO$lap==48,]$Distance,ALO[ALO$lap==48,]$Speed, col="red")
legend("topright", legend = c("Average speed", "Lap 48"), col=c("black", "red"), lty=c(1,1), cex=0.8)

Indeed, on this lap, Ferando Alonso braked abnormally at the start of the lap (400m). Moreover, the peak of the second main axis corresponds to this distance of around 400m.

It‚Äôs this braking that makes this lap different from the others.

If we return to the projection of laps on the axes, we can see that axis 1 separates laps on medium tires (black) from those on soft tires (red).

If we go back to the representation of the variance and the analysis that was carried out, we can then think that the type of tire will have an influence on braking and acceleration. To try and confirm this hypothesis, we look at which types of tire are used when braking at 2.5km.

for(i in 1:nrow(laps_alonso))
if(laps_alonso$Compound[i]=="MEDIUM"){
  laps_alonso$color[i]="black"
} else if(laps_alonso$Compound[i]=="SOFT"){
  laps_alonso$color[i]="red"
}

plot(seq(xrange[1],xrange[2],length=50),seq(yrange[1],yrange[2],length=50),type="n",main="Observed curves",xlab="Distance",ylab="Speed", xlim=c(2350, 2700),ylim=c(175,250))

legend("topright", legend = c("Medium", "Soft"), col=c("black", "red"), lty=c(1,1), cex=0.8)

for (i in unique(ALO$lap)){
  datap = ALO[which(ALO$lap==i),]
  lines(datap$Distance,datap$Speed,col=laps_alonso$color[which(laps_alonso$LapNumber==i)])
}

This graph shows that pre-braking speed is generally lower for laps on medium tires than on soft tires. This confirms our hypothesis.

5 Conclusion

From what we‚Äôve been able to observe, the braking moments at 250m, 800m and 2.5km are surely the places on the circuit where Ferando Alonso can gain (or lose) the most time on his lap. The type of tire will also influence his braking at these points.
